Philosopher and bigot alike are in their last resort driven to their creeds3 the only difference being that vvhile the creed of the philosopher offers its support uncon· ditionally and leaves him his liberty, with the free use of his faculties,—that of the bigot stipulates as the preliminary condition of its support, the absolute surrender of freedom. With eyes blinded and limbs fettered, he is held to his creed by the bonds of

authority, and so is only preserved from other ⁸ tyrannies by the subjugation of his soul to the greatest one of all. Nor can it be said that this matter of freedom is one of minor importance, and that it signifies little how rectitudo is preserved as long as it is preserved It signifies much; it signifies all: it signifies the whole difference between psychical development and psychical degeneration. Truth is mental food. By means of it the soul is nourished. As it enters, the mind expands and the psyche is developed in the same proportion.
